<br />
Just Try to Resist the Shadow by Jared Souer    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Ah, for the longest time, I have done nothing here.  But, when I thought of this seemingly unique idea (which I have no idea if it is unique), I came here for your honest opinions.<br />
<br />
For the Shadow side, of which this deck is based around, it uses a bunch of discard cards, like the Uruk Soldiers and Tower Luitenants, so that I can maybe, just maybe, deck them.  Up until the later points in the game, I try to keep a Irresistable Shadow in my hand until I can actually deck them, then I lay it down for the win, if I can get them 5 burdens.  This is where the Gaurds come in.  4 of those, hopefully 4 burdens, along with the starting bid and (again, hopefully) Worry, will result in the neccasary burdens.<br />
<br />
There is only one thing that absolutely KILLS this deck.  And the name of it is..........Courteous Halfling.  This will result in probably a loss if they use it.<br />
<br />
For the Free Peoples, the Dwarven Axes actually help the Shadow strategy very much.  There isn&#39;t much more than that, just basic, tank-like dwarf deck.  If I see that they use that Frodo, then I will try to run to site nine.  That, although, still doesn&#39;t work to well.<br />
<br />
So please give me your honest opinions on this one! </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
